is bounded laterally by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eciliary body\u003C/strong\u003E. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eiris\u003C/strong\u003E forms its anterior boundary, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Elens\u003C/strong\u003E forms its posterior boundary. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evitreous face\u003C/strong\u003E is posterior to the lens and does not form part of the posterior chamber. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ezonular fibres\u003C/strong\u003E (suspensory ligaments) connect the lens to the ciliary body but do not form a boundary of the posterior chamber.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior chamber is an important space filled with aqueous humor, which is produced by the ciliary processes. This fluid flows from the posterior chamber through the pupil into the anterior chamber, eventually draining via the trabecular meshwork at the iridocorneal angle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior chamber of the eye is bounded anteriorly by the iris and posteriorly by the lens.","The ciliary body forms the lateral boundary of the posterior chamber.","The posterior chamber contains aqueous humor and is continuous with the anterior chamber through the pupil."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16332"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/